abstract: Players in the category would receive up to $1.5 million, knowing that if they develop full-blown dementia they can receive as much as $1.5 million more.
snippet: Players in the category would receive up to $1.5 million, knowing that if they develop full-blown dementia they can receive as much as $1.5 million more.
lead_paragraph: A persistent criticism of the $765 million settlement the N.F.L. agreed to in August is that only retired players in the worst health will receive payouts.

abstract: Michael French, who struggled with the brain disease frontotemporal dementia, diagnosed in 2007, died at a Manhattan nursing home.
snippet: Michael French, who struggled with the brain disease frontotemporal dementia, diagnosed in 2007, died at a Manhattan nursing home.
lead_paragraph: Michael French, whose long struggle with the brain disease frontotemporal dementia was the subject of a 2012 New York Times article and video, died Nov. 30 at a nursing home in Manhattan. He was 73.
headline.main: Michael French, Who Battled a Rare Dementia, Dies at 73
headline.print_headline: One Mind’s Long Decay Finally Ends

abstract: High doses of vitamin E may help people with Alzheimer’s disease maintain the ability to perform routine daily tasks, a new study finds, even though it does not slow cognitive decline.
snippet: High doses of vitamin E may help people with Alzheimer’s disease maintain the ability to perform routine daily tasks, a new study finds, even though it does not slow cognitive decline.
lead_paragraph: Updated, 6:17 p.m. |
headline.main: Vitamin E Slows Decline of Some Alzheimer’s Patients in Study

abstract: Families often do not understand what a “do not hospitalize” order means, a small study finds.
snippet: Families often do not understand what a “do not hospitalize” order means, a small study finds.
lead_paragraph: The old man lashed out the first night he spent in the nursing home. His behavior was so alarming that staff transferred him to a nearby hospital for evaluation.
headline.main: A Misunderstood Directive

abstract: Alzheimer’s disease is scary, but that’s no reason to waste money on a test that really doesn’t help.
snippet: Alzheimer’s disease is scary, but that’s no reason to waste money on a test that really doesn’t help.
lead_paragraph: PHILADELPHIA — ALMOST every day I worry about whether my parents have Alzheimer’s. My dad is 86 and my mother is about to turn 80. Just because of their age they are at high risk for the disease, and I constantly wonder if their forgetfulness is “normal” or a sign of the worst.

abstract: Just when you thought there couldn’t be another caregiving memoir worth reading, “The Fifth Season” arrives.
snippet: Just when you thought there couldn’t be another caregiving memoir worth reading, “The Fifth Season” arrives.
lead_paragraph: I told myself I wasn’t going to write about any more memoirs, at least not for a while. The act of honoring thy aging father or mother has already generated so many magazine articles and op-eds and blogs and books, including Katie Hafner’s account of moving her mother into her home and Katy Butler’s story of her family’s struggle to deactivate the pacemaker that kept her father’s heart beating while his brain and the rest of his body failed.

abstract: An unusual survey reports that older wives often hold their stepchildren responsible for caregiving problems.
snippet: An unusual survey reports that older wives often hold their stepchildren responsible for caregiving problems.
lead_paragraph: Her husband’s dementia worsens. Bills are piling up, and knotty daily and long-term decisions must be confronted. The wife is exhausted, overwhelmed, lonely. She needs support from the family. So she turns to the adult children — his, from a previous marriage.
headline.main: Study Finds Wives Often Struggle With Stepchildren Over Caregiving

abstract: There’s no fixing this, whatever you call it. So I bake a cake.
snippet: There’s no fixing this, whatever you call it. So I bake a cake.
lead_paragraph: My mother lives in Scottsdale, Ariz., so packing for a summer 90th birthday visit was easy: Loose linen clothes, a sheet of baking parchment, and a three-ounce bar of Scharffen Berger bittersweet chocolate because my sister wasn’t sure she’d bought enough.

abstract: Professors at Johns Hopkins University plan to offer an online course in coping with dementia.
snippet: Professors at Johns Hopkins University plan to offer an online course in coping with dementia.
lead_paragraph: Recently, someone dear to me received the diagnosis of dementia, and I’ve been grappling with the frustrations of helping her adapt.
headline.main: Online Lessons in Dementia Management

abstract: HIgh blood glucose levels are tied to an increased risk of Alzheimer’s disease and vascular dementia in a new study.
snippet: HIgh blood glucose levels are tied to an increased risk of Alzheimer’s disease and vascular dementia in a new study.
lead_paragraph: People with diabetes face an increased risk of Alzheimer’s disease and other forms of dementia, a connection scientists and physicians have worried about for years. They still can’t explain it.
headline.main: High Blood Sugar Linked to Dementia

abstract: A push for early detection and treatment, even in the absence of cognitive symptoms, of the amyloid plaques that indicate a risk for Alzheimer’s and other dementias has some researchers worried.
snippet: A push for early detection and treatment, even in the absence of cognitive symptoms, of the amyloid plaques that indicate a risk for Alzheimer’s and other dementias has some researchers worried.
lead_paragraph: Marie Theriault started having trouble with her hands more than three years ago. She was the director of a day care center, but suddenly she couldn’t change diapers or tie shoelaces. She started dropping things.

abstract: The documentary “The United States of Football” follows retired players dealing with dementia and depression after a career of hard knocks.
snippet: The documentary “The United States of Football” follows retired players dealing with dementia and depression after a career of hard knocks.
lead_paragraph: “Would I allow my son to play football?” is the question that the sports journalist Sean Pamphilon positions at the center of “The United States of Football,” his documentary on the dangers of head injuries in that sport. He follows the stories of several retired N.F.L. players, living and dead, who had the degenerative brain disease chronic traumatic encephalopathy, which has been linked to repetitive blows to the head. Extreme dementia and depression set in before the disease slowly destroys the body. “What do you do with a 300-pound, 45-year-old person who’s out of control and is only going to get worse?” asks Lisa McHale, the widow of the Tampa Bay lineman Tom McHale.

lead_paragraph: The man complained of memory problems but seemed perfectly normal. No specialist he visited detected any decline.

headline.main: Dementia’s Signs May Come Early
headline.print_headline: Dementia’s Signs May Come Early

abstract: New studies from Denmark and Britain find that older people are getting healthier and experiencing less dementia.
snippet: New studies from Denmark and Britain find that older people are getting healthier and experiencing less dementia.
lead_paragraph: We talk about some grim stuff in this space, so when a bit of good news surfaces about aging, we want to celebrate.
headline.main: In Europe, Dementia Rates May Be Falling

abstract: Two new studies out of Europe have confirmed what researchers had long suspected: rates would fall and mental acuity improve as populations grew healthier and better educated.
snippet: Two new studies out of Europe have confirmed what researchers had long suspected: rates would fall and mental acuity improve as populations grew healthier and better educated.
lead_paragraph: A new study has found that dementia rates among people 65 and older in England and Wales have plummeted by 25 percent over the past two decades, to 6.2 percent from 8.3 percent, a trend that researchers say is probably occurring across developed countries and that could have major social and economic implications for families and societies.

abstract: Violent behavior often leads families to place people with dementia in care facilities.
snippet: Violent behavior often leads families to place people with dementia in care facilities.
lead_paragraph: For more than five years, Phyllis Edelstein managed to care for her husband Richard in their Long Island home as his dementia slowly progressed. She felt fortunate to have found, and to be able to pay for, a live-in couple to help her.
headline.main: When Aggression Follows Dementia

abstract: A spate of excellent movies about aging may reflect filmmakers’ dawning recognition of the way this global demographic shift affects all our lives.
snippet: A spate of excellent movies about aging may reflect filmmakers’ dawning recognition of the way this global demographic shift affects all our lives.
lead_paragraph: “She has her good days and her bad days, that’s all,” Craig Morrison, who is in his late 80s, testily tells his son. It’s an intensely self-sufficient man’s warning to back off, a we-don’t-need-anyone’s-help declaration that will sound familiar to many readers here.
headline.main: ‘Still Mine’ Adds to Movies on Aging

headline.print_headline: Fitness May Prevent Dementia

abstract: A new study adds to evidence of a link between late-life depression and dementia.
snippet: A new study adds to evidence of a link between late-life depression and dementia.
lead_paragraph: A large body of research has linked late-life depression to social isolation, poorer health and an increased risk of death. Now, a new study finds that depression is associated with subsequent vascular dementia and Alzheimer’s disease, conditions poised to expand dramatically with the aging population.
headline.main: Does Depression Contribute to Dementia?

abstract: There is no clear explanation why, but compared with individuals with normal hearing, those with hearing loss have an increased risk of developing dementia.
snippet: There is no clear explanation why, but compared with individuals with normal hearing, those with hearing loss have an increased risk of developing dementia.
lead_paragraph: At a party the other night, a fund-raiser for a literary magazine, I found myself in conversation with a well-known author whose work I greatly admire. I use the term “conversation” loosely. I couldn’t hear a word he said. But worse, the effort I was making to hear was using up so much brain power that I completely forgot the titles of his books.

headline.main: Ask Well: Exercises to Prevent Dementia?

abstract: The number of people with dementia and the cost of caring for them are skyrocketing at a rate that rarely occurs with a chronic disease, a new study suggests.
snippet: The number of people with dementia and the cost of caring for them are skyrocketing at a rate that rarely occurs with a chronic disease, a new study suggests.
lead_paragraph: The most rigorous study to date of how much it costs to care for Americans with dementia found that the financial burden is at least as high as that of heart disease or cancer, and is probably higher. And both the costs and the number of people with dementia will more than double within 30 years, skyrocketing at a rate that rarely occurs with a chronic disease.

abstract: Some specialized units for dementia care do manage to improve on traditional nursing home care, recent studies suggest.
snippet: Some specialized units for dementia care do manage to improve on traditional nursing home care, recent studies suggest.
lead_paragraph: By their euphemistic names, ye shall know them: The Memory Care Unit. The Reminiscence Neighborhood. Homestead.
headline.main: Studies Find Mixed Results for Dementia Units

abstract: Katherine Bouton talked about her own struggle with hearing loss, as well as new research that has found an association between hearing loss and dementia.
snippet: Katherine Bouton talked about her own struggle with hearing loss, as well as new research that has found an association between hearing loss and dementia.
lead_paragraph: This interview has been edited and condensed for space.

abstract: Ben Carey on what the research behind gaming and violence tells us — and what it doesn’t; John Tierney on eHarmony and the computerized search for love; Katherine Bouton shares a personal story of hearing loss and talks about how it might contribute to dementia.

headline.main: Gamers and School Violence, Algorithms of Love, Hearing Loss and Dementia

headline.main: Confronting the Specter of Alzheimer’s

abstract: Two doctors, one now a patient, write about impending dementia and end-of-life care.
snippet: Two doctors, one now a patient, write about impending dementia and end-of-life care.
lead_paragraph: This week, let me pass along some of the more absorbing blogs and Web sites I’ve come across recently, other corners of the online world where people are talking about aging and caregiving from very different perspectives.
headline.main: Two Blogs Worth Reading

snippet: A reader laments that she did not have the chance to say goodbye before her husband’s death.

headline.main: A Farewell to the Dying
headline.print_headline: A Farewell to the Dying

abstract: Children’s books bind together a mother and daughter.
snippet: Children’s books bind together a mother and daughter.
lead_paragraph: Even after the second stroke robbed Betty Woodruff, 96, of her sharp mind and memory, she fought to stay mentally active in the ways she had always loved, like participating in her regular bridge game.
headline.main: A Family Ritual Gains New Life

abstract: People with Alzheimer’s disease or mild cognitive impairment may be more susceptible to emotional cues from those around them.
snippet: People with Alzheimer’s disease or mild cognitive impairment may be more susceptible to emotional cues from those around them.
lead_paragraph: Jean McFee Raichle, 94, is a remarkably cheerful woman. She lives in an assisted living center in Seattle staffed by aides who are warm and nurturing. She exists in the moment, mostly untroubled by her Alzheimer’s disease.
headline.main: Empathy Without Boundaries

abstract: What families can do if the V.A. rejects a veteran’s claim for caregiving benefits.
snippet: What families can do if the V.A. rejects a veteran’s claim for caregiving benefits.
lead_paragraph: If you’ve been rejected for the Department of Veterans Affairs Aid and Attendance (A&A) benefit, there are steps you can take to get your application reconsidered. But first, a warning: Do not do what the V.A. denial letter suggests you do, as that may only bring you years more of delays. And second, you’ll need to invoke the spirit of Winston Churchill in his 1941 speech to the Harrow School: “Never give in — never, never, never, never, in nothing great or small, large or petty, never give in.”
headline.main: After the Denial Letter Arrives

abstract: Dementia doesn’t respect public stature or intellectual accomplishments.
snippet: Dementia doesn’t respect public stature or intellectual accomplishments.
lead_paragraph: The long list of roles Margaret Thatcher played during her 87 years — potent politician, free-market evangelist, labor antagonist, dominant global leader — includes the one she never publicly discussed: person with dementia.
headline.main: A Singular Life, an All Too Common End

abstract: Lower scores on tests of mental function were tied to exposure to common viruses and bacteria like herpes, cytomegalovirus, chlamydia and Helicobacter pylori.
snippet: Lower scores on tests of mental function were tied to exposure to common viruses and bacteria like herpes, cytomegalovirus, chlamydia and Helicobacter pylori.
lead_paragraph: A new study adds to the evidence that chronic infection, known to be associated with vascular disease, is also associated with poorer performance on tests of mental ability.

abstract: A judge on Tuesday will decide whether to grant the N.F.L.’s request to dismiss more than 200 cases filed by more than 4,000 former players who claim the league hid information about the dangers of head trauma.
snippet: A judge on Tuesday will decide whether to grant the N.F.L.’s request to dismiss more than 200 cases filed by more than 4,000 former players who claim the league hid information about the dangers of head trauma.
lead_paragraph: The N.F.L. will face off in court Tuesday against thousands of retirees in a case that will help determine the league’s role in caring for players with dementia and other neurodegenerative diseases.
headline.main: A Court Test for Suits About Head Trauma
headline.print_headline: A Court Test for Suits About Head Trauma

abstract: This spring, the Alzheimer’s Association plans to launch ‘social engagement’ groups nationwide for people with early-stage dementia.
snippet: This spring, the Alzheimer’s Association plans to launch ‘social engagement’ groups nationwide for people with early-stage dementia.
lead_paragraph: Three years ago, Kennard Lehmann walked out of a neurologist’s office in Sacramento, Calif., newly diagnosed with early-stage Alzheimer’s disease, a prescription in hand and absolutely no idea where to turn for help.

abstract: For the most robust brain health, it’s probably advisable to incorporate both aerobic and resistance training, two new studies in people and animals suggest.
snippet: For the most robust brain health, it’s probably advisable to incorporate both aerobic and resistance training, two new studies in people and animals suggest.
lead_paragraph: Two new experiments, one involving people and the other animals, suggest that regular exercise can substantially improve memory, although different types of exercise seem to affect the brain quite differently. The news may offer consolation for the growing numbers of us who are entering age groups most at risk for cognitive decline.

lead_paragraph: President Obama injected some reality into the endless Super Bowl rituals glorifying the game with his candid remarks about the long-term damage from concussions suffered on the playing field. Mr. Obama said the sport will most likely have to change in order to reduce the traumatic hits that can leave players suffering dementia years after their careers have ended.
headline.main: Nagging Concerns Before the Big Game
headline.print_headline: Nagging Concerns Before the Big Game

abstract: Federal officials said Johnson & Johnson promoted the antipsychotic drug as a way to treat dementia patients for many ailments, when it was only approved for schizophrenia.
snippet: Federal officials said Johnson & Johnson promoted the antipsychotic drug as a way to treat dementia patients for many ailments, when it was only approved for schizophrenia.
lead_paragraph: Johnson & Johnson has agreed to pay more than $2.2 billion in criminal and civil fines to settle accusations that it improperly promoted the antipsychotic drug Risperdal to older adults, children and people with developmental disabilities, the Justice Department said on Monday.

abstract: The federal agency overseeing Medicare is reluctant to endorse, or pay for brain scans to diagnose Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: The federal agency overseeing Medicare is reluctant to endorse, or pay for brain scans to diagnose Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: For all the hue and cry about detecting the earliest signs of Alzheimer’s disease, the federal Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services has concluded that amyloid brain scans for the purpose of diagnosing Alzheimer’s disease are not ready for prime time.
headline.main: Decision Casts Doubt on Brain Scans for Alzheimer’s

abstract: The new policy, which takes effect on Jan. 16, could pave the way for thousands of veterans to file claims.
snippet: The new policy, which takes effect on Jan. 16, could pave the way for thousands of veterans to file claims.
lead_paragraph: The Department of Veterans Affairs has approved new regulations to make it easier for veterans to receive health care and compensation for certain illnesses, including Parkinsonism, dementia, and depression, which have been linked to traumatic brain injury.

abstract: A proposal to ease testing requirements is seductive but raises concerns about safety.
snippet: A proposal to ease testing requirements is seductive but raises concerns about safety.
lead_paragraph: The Food and Drug Administration has proposed lowering the bar for approving drugs to treat people at the earliest stages of Alzheimer’s disease, before they have developed any serious impairment or overt dementia. The goal is commendable — to find ways to prevent or slow the progression of this terrible disease before it can rob people of their mental capacities. But the proposal raises troubling questions as to whether the agency would end up approving drugs that provide little or no clinical benefit yet cause harmful side effects in people who take the medications for extended periods.
headline.main: Drugs for Early-Stage Alzheimer’s
headline.print_headline: Drugs for Early-Stage Alzheimer’s

abstract: Eighteen new lists of “Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question” were released last week, and they include the recommendations from geriatricians and palliative care specialists.
snippet: Eighteen new lists of “Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question” were released last week, and they include the recommendations from geriatricians and palliative care specialists.
lead_paragraph: The Choosing Wisely campaign, an initiative by the American Board of Internal Medicine Foundation in partnership with Consumer Reports, kicked off last spring. It is an attempt to alert both doctors and patients to problematic and commonly overused medical tests, procedures and treatments.
headline.main: For the Elderly, Medical Procedures to Avoid

abstract: A new documentary airing on PBS explores the shortcomings of the assisted living industry.
snippet: A new documentary airing on PBS explores the shortcomings of the assisted living industry.
lead_paragraph: Assisted living underwent a big growth spurt in the 1990s as major corporations built and bought facilities, and almost ever since advocacy groups and researchers have been warning that however attractive these places look — chandeliered lobbies, pleasant individual apartments, the inevitable gazebo outside — the care they provide tends to be mediocre at best.

abstract: The theater veteran talks about her role as a biophysicist battling dementia in Joe Mantello’s Broadway play, “The Other Place.”
snippet: The theater veteran talks about her role as a biophysicist battling dementia in Joe Mantello’s Broadway play, “The Other Place.”
lead_paragraph: The theater veteran Laurie Metcalf, best known as Jackie, Roseanne Barr’s high-strung sidekick sister on the popular 1990s sitcom “Roseanne,” is back on Broadway. Metcalf, an Emmy Award-winning actress, is currently reprising her leading role as Juliana Smithton, a biophysicist battling dementia in Sharr White’s “The Other Place,” running through March 3 at Manhattan Theater Club‘s Samuel J. Friedman’s Theater. In the new drama directed by Joe Mantello — and in approximately 80 minutes — Metcalf takes the audience on a gut-wrenching ride as her nefarious disease leaves a path of heartbreaking destruction. Her performance is haunting and left T with many questions, which Metcalf generously answered.
headline.main: Talking Talent | Laurie Metcalf

abstract: Social isolation can adversely affect health, undermining the ability to self-regulate, raising stress and increasing inflammation, studies show.
snippet: Social isolation can adversely affect health, undermining the ability to self-regulate, raising stress and increasing inflammation, studies show.
lead_paragraph: I now know why I gained more than 30 pounds in my early 20s: I was lonely. I had left my beloved alma mater upstate for graduate school and a job in the Upper Midwest. I knew no one and felt like a fish out of water.

abstract: Patty Cassidy, a horticultural therapist, will answer readers’ questions about gardening in your later years.
snippet: Patty Cassidy, a horticultural therapist, will answer readers’ questions about gardening in your later years.
lead_paragraph: This week’s Ask an Expert features Patty Cassidy, who will answer questions on how to use outdoor spaces and gardens to improve health and well-being, and what to do when the physical challenges of aging or mental challenges such as dementia and Alzheimer’s come into play.

abstract: After months of exchanges of information, a woman who had a stroke is denied benefits under a long-term care policy. Her son-in-law asks the Haggler to intervene.
snippet: After months of exchanges of information, a woman who had a stroke is denied benefits under a long-term care policy. Her son-in-law asks the Haggler to intervene.
lead_paragraph: OUR episode about Whirlpool’s grudging approach to customer service, as illuminated by the tale of a faulty microwave, prompted more than a dozen e-mails of the oh-you-think-that’s-bad? variety. Most were mundane variations on a theme of Whirlpool indifference, incompetence or both. But one stood out. It came from Shira London, a librarian in Baltimore, and the owner of a Whirlpool refrigerator that makes a very loud buzzing noise.

abstract: The actress, accompanied by Katherine Cherbas on cello, sings “Me and My Mother” from Sara Cooper and Zach Redler’s musical.
snippet: The actress, accompanied by Katherine Cherbas on cello, sings “Me and My Mother” from Sara Cooper and Zach Redler’s musical.
lead_paragraph: In the musical “The Memory Show,” Leslie Kritzer plays a woman, identified simply as Daughter, who has moved home to take care of her aging mother, who is in the early stages of Alzheimer’s disease. In the song “Me and My Mother,” Daughter has just witnessed her mother’s first major episode of dementia. The show, with a book and lyrics by Sara Cooper and music by Zach Redler, continues through Saturday at the Duke on 42nd Street.
headline.main: In Performance: Leslie Kritzer of ‘The Memory Show’

abstract: The N.F.L. effectively sets the policies for youth football players, an invisible constituency that will see no compensation from Thursday’s settlement over head injuries.
snippet: The N.F.L. effectively sets the policies for youth football players, an invisible constituency that will see no compensation from Thursday’s settlement over head injuries.
lead_paragraph: When more than 4,000 retired players agreed to accept $765 million to settle their lawsuit with the N.F.L., the league was able to cling to its most valuable claim of all — that it never ignored or obscured the risks of concussions.

abstract: The lack of daily oral care in nursing facilities is almost universally overlooked, experts say, and studies suggest that it may contribute to pneumonia, a leading killer of institutionalized older people.
snippet: The lack of daily oral care in nursing facilities is almost universally overlooked, experts say, and studies suggest that it may contribute to pneumonia, a leading killer of institutionalized older people.
lead_paragraph: Katherine Ford visited her father, Dean Piercy, a World War II veteran with dementia, at a nursing home in Roanoke, Va., for months before she noticed the dust on his electric toothbrush. His teeth, she found, had not been brushed recently, so she began doing it herself after their lunches together.

abstract: Some family members of players involved in the concussion lawsuit were mostly positive about the outcome while the response from a few current and retired players was mixed.
snippet: Some family members of players involved in the concussion lawsuit were mostly positive about the outcome while the response from a few current and retired players was mixed.
lead_paragraph: When news circulated Thursday that the N.F.L. had agreed to pay $765 million to settle a concussion lawsuit, it was met with mostly positive reactions from some family members of players involved in the suit.

snippet: Some family members of players involved in the concussion lawsuit were mostly positive about the outcome while the response from a few current and retired players was mixed.
lead_paragraph: When news circulated Thursday that the N.F.L. had agreed to pay $765 million to settle a concussion lawsuit, it was met with mostly positive reactions from some family members of players involved in the suit.

lead_paragraph: THE SIGNATURE OF ALL THINGS,  by Elizabeth Gilbert. (Viking, $28.95.) In this winning novel by the author of “Eat, Pray, Love,” a botanist’s hunger for explanations carries her through the better part of Darwin’s century, and to Tahiti.

abstract: A new study by researchers at Johns Hopkins Medicine suggests that elderly people with compromised hearing are at risk of developing cognitive deficits — problems with memory and thinking — sooner than those whose hearing is intact.
snippet: A new study by researchers at Johns Hopkins Medicine suggests that elderly people with compromised hearing are at risk of developing cognitive deficits — problems with memory and thinking — sooner than those whose hearing is intact.
lead_paragraph: There’s another reason to be concerned about hearing loss — one of the most common health conditions in older adults and one of the most widely undertreated. A new study by researchers at Johns Hopkins Medicine suggests that elderly people with compromised hearing are at risk of developing cognitive deficits — problems with memory and thinking — sooner than those whose hearing is intact.
headline.main: Study Links Cognitive Deficits, Hearing Loss

lead_paragraph: ROTH UNBOUND: A Writer and His Books,  by Claudia Roth Pierpont. (Farrar, Straus & Giroux, $27.) This clever account is an authorized critical life of the old school, but invaluably topped up with reported comments from the Roth of today.

abstract: For patients and doctors, new guidelines that include the elimination of target levels for “bad cholesterol” represent a surprising change in perspective.
snippet: For patients and doctors, new guidelines that include the elimination of target levels for “bad cholesterol” represent a surprising change in perspective.
lead_paragraph: Steven L. Zweibel has been taking a statin drug to lower his cholesterol for seven years. It has worked, and he has suffered no problems or side effects.

abstract: Research building on data from the Women’s Health Initiative confirms that the risks of hormones outweigh the benefits, but that their use is sometimes appropriate.
snippet: Research building on data from the Women’s Health Initiative confirms that the risks of hormones outweigh the benefits, but that their use is sometimes appropriate.
lead_paragraph: Hormone therapy for menopause is one of the most divisive subjects in medicine, hailed by some as a boon to women’s comfort and well-being, vilified by others as a threat to health.

abstract: Two fraternal detectives wrestle with murder and morality in Nick Murphy’s crime drama “Blood.”
snippet: Two fraternal detectives wrestle with murder and morality in Nick Murphy’s crime drama “Blood.”
lead_paragraph: Trying to cram a six-part BBC television series into a 92-minute movie means inevitable narrative tinkering, but “Blood” feels more damaged than most. Dark, airless and packed with psychological hurt that seems to spring from nowhere, this angry morality play, tucked inside a police procedural, suffers from a crippling lack of back story and characters whose relationships are fraught with unexplained complexity.

abstract: Mr. Holland was the first staff member of the Federal Reserve System to be appointed directly to its Board of Governors.
snippet: Mr. Holland was the first staff member of the Federal Reserve System to be appointed directly to its Board of Governors.
lead_paragraph: Robert C. Holland, the first staff member of the Federal Reserve System to be appointed directly to its Board of Governors, died on Thursday at his home in Centreville, Va. He was 87.

abstract: A dirt-poor Texas family hires a secretive handyman to care for a son with cerebral palsy in the drama “This Is Where We Live.”
snippet: A dirt-poor Texas family hires a secretive handyman to care for a son with cerebral palsy in the drama “This Is Where We Live.”
lead_paragraph: A man of few words is drawn to a family with few blessings in “This Is Where We Live,” a dusty drama about soldiering on without giving in.

abstract: Adult children who have overseen their parents’ care say that besides physical and emotional strains, there are financial effects that can include a loss of job mobility.
snippet: Adult children who have overseen their parents’ care say that besides physical and emotional strains, there are financial effects that can include a loss of job mobility.
lead_paragraph: THROUGH the 1990s, Patrick Quirke’s career was sailing along. Every few years, he would be promoted at the transportation company where he worked and move to another city. He said he had every reason to believe that he would be promoted to the company’s headquarters in a few more moves. Then, his parents’ health started to decline.

abstract: Retired players deserve the chance to prove in court the link between the violent professional game and head trauma and that the league failed to protect them.
snippet: Retired players deserve the chance to prove in court the link between the violent professional game and head trauma and that the league failed to protect them.
lead_paragraph: More than 4,000 retired players are suing the National Football League for failing to protect players from chronic risks of head injuries routinely inflicted in professional football games — and then willfully concealing those risks from players. In a brief summarizing the players’ position, lawyers say that serious head injuries “cause neurocognitive decline, permanent mental disability, and even death.”

abstract: More data on how the elderly fare with dialysis.
snippet: More data on how the elderly fare with dialysis.
lead_paragraph: Dialysis is difficult for people of any age, but especially for frail older adults with multiple chronic conditions such as diabetes, heart disease and dementia — the patients least likely to have their lives extended significantly by this treatment.
headline.main: Dialysis Takes a Toll

abstract: Mr. Lyons covered science, Congress and the United Nations in nearly 30 years at The New York Times.
snippet: Mr. Lyons covered science, Congress and the United Nations in nearly 30 years at The New York Times.
lead_paragraph: Richard D. Lyons, who covered science, Congress and the United Nations during almost 30 years as a reporter for The New York Times, died on Wednesday at his home in Charleston, S.C. He was 84.

abstract: Mr. Oliver covered major world events, like the conflicts in Laos, Cambodia and Vietnam, the Middle East peace talks in 1977 and the Civil War in El Salvador, for NBC News for more than 25 years.
snippet: Mr. Oliver covered major world events, like the conflicts in Laos, Cambodia and Vietnam, the Middle East peace talks in 1977 and the Civil War in El Salvador, for NBC News for more than 25 years.
lead_paragraph: Don Oliver, who reached a nightly national audience as a correspondent covering major events for NBC News for more than 25 years, died on Tuesday in Spokane, Wash. He was 76.

abstract: When it came time for Sunny Harper-Owen to plan an event for her women’s group, she couldn’t do it. Then her female friends formed a new group — this one to support her.
snippet: When it came time for Sunny Harper-Owen to plan an event for her women’s group, she couldn’t do it. Then her female friends formed a new group — this one to support her.
lead_paragraph: The Supporting Sunny Group had planned this luncheon carefully. Because Sunny Harper-Owen, their longtime friend, warmly remembered the years she spent in Paris, the group had decided on a French theme and were bringing quiche, onion soup and chocolate mousse.
headline.main: For the Love of Sunny

abstract: I like the newer, blunter me. I sense a whole new world opening up.

lead_paragraph: You might not know this unless we have met, but I am an exceptionally polite person.

abstract: Officials said they would introduce legislation this week to increase oversight of programs that have taken advantage of Medicaid payments by luring relatively healthy clients.
snippet: Officials said they would introduce legislation this week to increase oversight of programs that have taken advantage of Medicaid payments by luring relatively healthy clients.
lead_paragraph: New York City officials said on Thursday that they would introduce legislation to crack down on Medicaid-supported senior day care centers that lure relatively healthy clients with enticements like free takeout food and even cash.

abstract: A study finds that prolonged use of the drugs can lead to anemia, neurological problems or dementia.
snippet: A study finds that prolonged use of the drugs can lead to anemia, neurological problems or dementia.
lead_paragraph: People who use certain acid-suppressing drugs for two years or longer are at increased risk of vitamin B12 deficiency, which can lead to anemia, neurological problems or dementia, researchers reported on Tuesday.

abstract: Repeated blows to the head of the N.F.L. guard Ralph Wenzel led to the dementia that he developed later in life. His wife, Eleanor Perfetto, watched the downward spiral that led to his death.
snippet: Repeated blows to the head of the N.F.L. guard Ralph Wenzel led to the dementia that he developed later in life. His wife, Eleanor Perfetto, watched the downward spiral that led to his death.
lead_paragraph: ANNAPOLIS, Md. — The end of Ralph Wenzel as his wife knew him began in January 2007. They were descending a flight of stairs at San Francisco International Airport, on their way to the baggage claim, after a two-week trip to Hawaii.

abstract: The new HBO comedy “Getting On,” starring Laurie Metcalf, aims to depict a true, if irreverent, look at elder care in a California hospital.
snippet: The new HBO comedy “Getting On,” starring Laurie Metcalf, aims to depict a true, if irreverent, look at elder care in a California hospital.
lead_paragraph: The rules for depicting the frail elderly on television are fairly clear: it must be done with a gauzy somberness. Dementia and nursing homes and such are something to be whispered about and handled with kid gloves rather than considered a fact of life.

abstract: In “Every Day a Visitor,” the residents of a retirement home decide to play an all-encompassing game, and in certain ways, it saves their lives.
snippet: In “Every Day a Visitor,” the residents of a retirement home decide to play an all-encompassing game, and in certain ways, it saves their lives.
lead_paragraph: Ending up in a retirement home could be joyous — if you’ve always wanted to relive dorm life and would like it even better with everybody having gotten cranky and lost both their youthful good looks and their hearing. (“You have to say everything twice in this place.”) And with no choice about which drugs you take or when. Richard Abrons apparently gave this prospect some thought before writing “Every Day a Visitor,” which Woodie King Jr.’s New Federal Theater is presenting at the Clurman Theater with a colorful, lovable and mostly mature cast.

lead_paragraph: Removing an aged parent or grandparent from a home that’s no longer safe or convenient is never easy.

abstract: Patients with certain conditions receive better treatment if they see a nurse practitioner in addition to a doctor, according to a new study, but professional territoriality and mistrust have long prevented progress.
snippet: Patients with certain conditions receive better treatment if they see a nurse practitioner in addition to a doctor, according to a new study, but professional territoriality and mistrust have long prevented progress.
lead_paragraph: When it comes to providing health care for an aging nation, the bad news is no longer news. We already lack sufficient numbers of geriatricians and other professionals — nurses, social workers, pharmacists, aides — trained to care for the elderly, and the shortage is projected to increase.
headline.main: In the Doctor’s Office, a Neglected Resource

abstract: J. Smith-Cameron, who played Jane in the first three Apple family plays, will not return to the role.
snippet: J. Smith-Cameron, who played Jane in the first three Apple family plays, will not return to the role.
lead_paragraph: The Apple family of Rhinebeck, N.Y., is breaking up. Well, sort of: The Public Theater announced on Thursday that its ambitious production of Richard Nelson’s four-part “Apple Family Plays” would not include the actress J. Smith-Cameron, who played the sister Jane in the first three. They had their premieres at the Public during the falls of 2010, 2011 and 2012; the fourth play, “Regular Singing,” will run in repertory this fall with the earlier plays, which drew widespread critical acclaim for their portrait of a politically disillusioned family of four siblings and their beloved uncle, whom they are slowly losing to dementia.

abstract: Paperback books of particular interest.
snippet: Paperback books of particular interest.
lead_paragraph: ALL GONE: A Memoir of My Mother’s Dementia. With Refreshments,  by Alex Witchel. (Riverhead, $16.) In this unflinching memoir, Witchel, a staff writer for The New York Times Magazine, describes how her once vibrant mother slowly began “disappearing in plain sight.” With its cast of vibrantly portrayed relatives and recipes passed down by Witchel’s mother and grandmother, “All Gone” is “a powerful affirmation of family bonds,” Maggie Scarf wrote in the Book Review.

abstract: Twitter lights up over the actress’ rambling, riveting speech at the Golden Globe Awards.
snippet: Twitter lights up over the actress’ rambling, riveting speech at the Golden Globe Awards.
lead_paragraph: THE Golden Globe Awards started out being all about Tina Fey and Amy Poehler — perhaps the best award-show hosts ever — but by evening’s end most of the talk was of Jodie Foster and the rambling, riveting speech (watched by her date, a stone-faced Mel Gibson) in which she seemed to simultaneously come out of the closet and announce her retirement from acting. On Twitter, Ms. Foster’s speech brought praise for its bravery as well as derision for not being brave enough.

abstract: With a growing population of Americans over the age of 65, but a lack of trained home health care workers, more and more people could opt to hire robots to do the job.
snippet: With a growing population of Americans over the age of 65, but a lack of trained home health care workers, more and more people could opt to hire robots to do the job.
lead_paragraph: In the opening scene of the movie “Robot & Frank,” which takes place in the near future, Frank, an elderly man who lives alone, is arguing with his son about going to a medical center for Alzheimer’s treatment when the son interrupts him. “I brought you something,” he says to Frank. Then the son pulls a large, white humanoid robot from the trunk of his car.

abstract: In a closely watched case, a judge is expected to decide soon whether to dismiss a lawsuit brought by retired players alleging that the N.F.L. intentionally misled them about the dangers of head injuries.
snippet: In a closely watched case, a judge is expected to decide soon whether to dismiss a lawsuit brought by retired players alleging that the N.F.L. intentionally misled them about the dangers of head injuries.
lead_paragraph: Before the N.F.L. regular season begins next Thursday, the league will get a clearer picture of what may be its biggest worry: the lawsuit brought by more than 4,500 retired players alleging that the N.F.L. intentionally misled them about the dangers of head injuries.

abstract: First novels by Emma Chapman and Fiona McFarlane consider women on the verge of breakdown.
snippet: First novels by Emma Chapman and Fiona McFarlane consider women on the verge of breakdown.
lead_paragraph: The title of Emma Chapman’s first novel, “How to Be a Good Wife,” is beyond ironic. What we encounter here in Marta Bjornstad is a woman clinging to domesticity as though to a flimsy plank in a turbulent sea. Marta is going under, and the power of this extraordinary book resides in large part in its unwavering focus on her deepening dislocation from the world around her, from her adult son and in particular from her husband.

lead_paragraph: LONDON — Doctors in England will soon be prescribing books as well as pills to patients suffering from anxiety and depression.

abstract: The $33.2 million grant will help finance a clinical trial to test a treatment on people 60 to 75 who have no symptoms of the disease, but do have two copies of a gene known to greatly increase the risk of getting it.
snippet: The $33.2 million grant will help finance a clinical trial to test a treatment on people 60 to 75 who have no symptoms of the disease, but do have two copies of a gene known to greatly increase the risk of getting it.
lead_paragraph: In the most significant sign yet of a broad shift in the focus of Alzheimer’s research from treating to preventing the disease, the federal government announced on Wednesday its largest grant so far to test an Alzheimer’s drug on healthy people at greatest risk for the most common form of the disease.

abstract: Patty Cassidy, a horticultural therapist, answers readers’ questions about grass, rock gardens, gardening for people with dementia and other subjects.
snippet: Patty Cassidy, a horticultural therapist, answers readers’ questions about grass, rock gardens, gardening for people with dementia and other subjects.
lead_paragraph: Patty Cassidy, the author of “The Illustrated Practical Guide to Gardening for Seniors: How to Maintain Your Outside Space With Ease Into Retirement and Beyond” (2011, Anness), has been answering readers’ questions about aging and gardening. Her first set of answers is here.

lead_paragraph: Debra Drelich, a specialist in geriatric care, has been answering readers’ readers’ questions about assisted living and other special living arrangements for aging relatives. Part 1 of her answers can be read here. Part 2 can be read here.

abstract: The end of the inquiry into allegations that former President Nicolas Sarkozy had manipulated an heiress into financing his campaign removed a potential obstacle to a political return.
snippet: The end of the inquiry into allegations that former President Nicolas Sarkozy had manipulated an heiress into financing his campaign removed a potential obstacle to a political return.
lead_paragraph: PARIS — French magistrates said Monday they were dropping an investigation into charges that former President Nicolas Sarkozy had manipulated a fragile heiress into financing his 2007 campaign, removing a potential obstacle to the political return that Mr. Sarkozy is widely assumed to be planning.
headline.main: French Judges Drop Investigation Into Charges Against Sarkozy
headline.print_headline: French Judges Drop Investigation Into Charges Against Sarkozy

abstract: The Senate Special Committee on Aging has started a consumer hotline designed to help track scams targeting the elderly.
snippet: The Senate Special Committee on Aging has started a consumer hotline designed to help track scams targeting the elderly.
lead_paragraph: The letters arrive almost daily, on official-looking letterhead from a supposed charity, or from the J.M.D. Major Cash Disbursement Office. More blatantly, letters sometimes come from an outfit called Mountains of Money. They announce that the 85-year-old man to whom they’re addressed has won a prize — the amount seems to hover around $11,000 — and explain that to claim it, he has to fill out a form, often complete with a “verification code,” and send it in with a check for $6 or $7.
headline.main: A New Way to Report Fraud

abstract: Therapists said they often encountered symptoms of trauma among caregivers, even though research documenting this phenomenon is scarce.
snippet: Therapists said they often encountered symptoms of trauma among caregivers, even though research documenting this phenomenon is scarce.
lead_paragraph: I recently wrote about caregivers who experienced symptoms of traumatic-like stress, and readers responded with heart-rending stories. Many described being haunted by distress long after a relative died.

abstract: A new novel examines the complicated lives of seniors living in a universe all their own.
snippet: A new novel examines the complicated lives of seniors living in a universe all their own.
lead_paragraph: “Who in the hell wants dinner at 5:30?” wonders Rachel Silverman, a sharp Boston lawyer who has mysteriously washed up in the fictional Pine Haven Retirement Community in the nonfictional Fulton, N.C.
headline.main: The Retirement Home, Alive With Intrigue

abstract: Long-term care insurance is becoming increasingly complex and expensive, and it can be difficult to separate emotions from the financial considerations.
snippet: Long-term care insurance is becoming increasingly complex and expensive, and it can be difficult to separate emotions from the financial considerations.
lead_paragraph: ANDY SHAPIRO had never given much thought to whether he would need help with daily activities as he aged. After all, the 61-year-old software consultant figured, he kept himself in good shape.
headline.main: Expense and Emotions in Preparing for Long-Term Care
headline.print_headline: Expense and Emotions in Preparing for Long-Term Care

abstract: As rentals are turned into condos, negotiations can turn into lawsuits.
snippet: As rentals are turned into condos, negotiations can turn into lawsuits.
lead_paragraph: On first blush, it looks like Carol Cohen, a top residential broker in Manhattan who has counted the fashion designer Vera Wang and the publishing scion Lachlan Murdoch as clients, has a great setup. She lives with her husband in a sprawling two-bedroom apartment on a prime block on Park Avenue, for which she pays about $3,000 a month in rent, far less than the $9,500 a month a nearby two-bedroom on Park Avenue costs.

abstract: New companies are coming up with ways to make smartphones into devices to monitor the foot traffic in stores or keep track of Alzheimer’s patients with the kind of technology used in house arrests. With the right incentives, people might even choose to be watched.
snippet: New companies are coming up with ways to make smartphones into devices to monitor the foot traffic in stores or keep track of Alzheimer’s patients with the kind of technology used in house arrests. With the right incentives, people might even choo...
lead_paragraph: Following people online, with cookies, tagged pixels and even voluntarily given information, has been a big business. Now much of the same technology is moving into the physical world.

abstract: Jill McCorkle returns to the fictional Fulton, N.C., in her sixth novel.
snippet: Jill McCorkle returns to the fictional Fulton, N.C., in her sixth novel.
lead_paragraph: From the knowing grandmother in the novel “Tending to Virginia” to the failing mother stressing out her daughter in the short story “Going Away Shoes,” elderly characters have always played their parts in Jill McCorkle’s small-town, intergenerational fiction. But the “manly voice” with “pipes and whistles in his sound,” as Shakespeare put it, reverberates in its own distinctive fashion in the retirement home setting of McCorkle’s new novel, where the yoga class finds “a whole roomful of old folks breathing deeply and chanting — one sounding like a sewing machine and another a squirrel.”

abstract: “Still Mine” is a love story about a couple in their late 80s who are keenly aware that after spending 61 years together and raising seven children, their time is running out.
snippet: “Still Mine” is a love story about a couple in their late 80s who are keenly aware that after spending 61 years together and raising seven children, their time is running out.
lead_paragraph: “Still Mine,” like Michael Haneke’s “Amour” and Sarah Polley’s “Away From Her,” is an old-age love story told with minimal sentimentality. If “Amour,” with its unflinching vision of dementia, is the toughest of the three, and “Away From Her” is the saddest, “Still Mine,” directed and written by Michael McGowan, has a similar spiky integrity. Dry-eyed and observant, it refuses to pity Craig and Irene Morrison (James Cromwell and Geneviève Bujold), the aged couple at its center.

abstract: After the stock market crash of 2008 and a collapsing housing bubble diminished the value of many nest eggs, the cost of long-term care is now a concern for many aging Americans.
snippet: After the stock market crash of 2008 and a collapsing housing bubble diminished the value of many nest eggs, the cost of long-term care is now a concern for many aging Americans.
lead_paragraph: FEW sticker shocks are as bracing as the price of hiring someone to help with the simplest activities — bathing, toilet use, dressing, eating and moving. Whether recovering from surgery or a stroke or suffering a chronic illness like arthritis, those needing skilled help need deep pockets indeed.

abstract: An Amsterdam Avenue comfort-food spot that became a destination is closing in January.
snippet: An Amsterdam Avenue comfort-food spot that became a destination is closing in January.
lead_paragraph: Carol Baer opened the Popover Café on Amsterdam Avenue in July 1981, using hot plates and household convection ovens. Over the course of 32 years it has become one of those places where locals line up for weekend cholesterol, for reasons that might elude an outsider. “Everyone always got treated the same,” Ms. Baer, 68, said last week in the restaurant’s yellow and red dining room, which she acknowledged was in need of an update. “Streisand waited in line. Warren Beatty waited in line.”

abstract: The National Institutes of Health has decided part of a grant from the N.F.L. to study brain injuries will go to two groups studying chronic traumatic encephalopathy, or C.T.E., in living patients.
snippet: The National Institutes of Health has decided part of a grant from the N.F.L. to study brain injuries will go to two groups studying chronic traumatic encephalopathy, or C.T.E., in living patients.
lead_paragraph: The National Institutes of Health outlined Monday how it planned to use part of a $30 million grant from the N.F.L. to finance a series of research projects designed to answer some of the most vexing questions about how and why athletes sustain traumatic brain injuries.

abstract: Researchers thus far have to use tissue obtained posthumously to diagnose the degenerative brain disease that has bedeviled those who have sustained repeated hits to the head.
snippet: Researchers thus far have to use tissue obtained posthumously to diagnose the degenerative brain disease that has bedeviled those who have sustained repeated hits to the head.
lead_paragraph: For years, researchers have had to use tissue obtained posthumously to diagnose chronic traumatic encephalopathy, or C.T.E., the degenerative brain disease that has bedeviled athletes, soldiers and others who have sustained repeated head hits and concussions.

abstract: Too many older adults simply can’t lay hands on their advance care directives when they need to.
snippet: Too many older adults simply can’t lay hands on their advance care directives when they need to.
lead_paragraph: Nancy Wagner, a social worker at Monmouth Medical Center in Long Branch, N.J., encounters this frustration at least once a week: A patient arrives in the emergency room and tells the inquiring staff that yes, she has indeed prepared and signed an advance directive. But, well, she doesn’t have it with her.

abstract: America's obsession with football crosses social and political divides and makes a hefty profit, but players' bodies are paying the price.

abstract: Major medical specialty groups recommended that doctors greatly reduce their use of 90 widely used but largely unnecessary tests and treatments.
snippet: Major medical specialty groups recommended that doctors greatly reduce their use of 90 widely used but largely unnecessary tests and treatments.

abstract: Terence Blanchard’s jazzy “Champion” had its premiere this week at Opera Theater of Saint Louis.
snippet: Terence Blanchard’s jazzy “Champion” had its premiere this week at Opera Theater of Saint Louis.
lead_paragraph: ST. LOUIS — Toward the end of Terence Blanchard’s “Champion,” which received its premiere this week at the Opera Theater of Saint Louis here, the protagonist, Emile Griffith, relives the terror of being attacked by homophobic thugs. “I killed a man and the world forgives me; I love a man and the world wants to kill me,” he sings despairingly.

abstract: “Frances and Bernard” by Carlene Bauer is a novel told in letters between characters based, both in temperament and biographical detail, on the writers Flannery O’Connor and Robert Lowell.
snippet: “Frances and Bernard” by Carlene Bauer is a novel told in letters between characters based, both in temperament and biographical detail, on the writers Flannery O’Connor and Robert Lowell.
lead_paragraph: “Flannery, I love you very much,” the poet Robert Lowell wrote to his friend Flannery O’Connor in 1954. He hastened to add parenthetically, “This isn’t a proposal, I have other eggs to fry.” In her own letter to “A.,” in 1956, O’Connor said of the troubled Lowell, “I feel almost too much about him to get to be able to get to the heart of it. He is a kind of grief to me.”

abstract: Dr. Wright defied racial barriers in a profession long dominated by white men and helped found the American Society of Clinical Oncology.
snippet: Dr. Wright defied racial barriers in a profession long dominated by white men and helped found the American Society of Clinical Oncology.
lead_paragraph: Dr. Jane C. Wright, a pioneering oncologist who helped elevate chemotherapy from a last resort for cancer patients to an often viable treatment option, died on Feb. 19 at her home in Guttenberg, N.J. She was 93.

abstract: In “Paradise: Love,” a middle-age single mother in Austria treats herself to a birthday trip to a coastal resort in Kenya.
snippet: In “Paradise: Love,” a middle-age single mother in Austria treats herself to a birthday trip to a coastal resort in Kenya.
lead_paragraph: The Austrian writer and director Ulrich Seidl is one of a number of European filmmakers — less a school than a tendency — for whom sadism is a tool of ethical and political enlightenment. Like his compatriot Michael Haneke (most notably in “Caché,” “Code Unknown” and both versions of “Funny Games”) and the Danish provocateur Lars von Trier (in his pseudo-American movies “Dancer in the Dark,” “Dogville” and “Manderlay”), Mr. Seidl sets out to expose the bad faith and complacency of the liberal West, and to rub his viewers’ noses in their own complicity with the exploitative cruelty of the current world order.

abstract: More than one-third of older adults reported some form of verbal abuse from family members and paid helpers in a recent study.
snippet: More than one-third of older adults reported some form of verbal abuse from family members and paid helpers in a recent study.
lead_paragraph: People may feel ashamed or afraid to talk about abuse, including the verbal kind, so the researchers from Northeastern University asked their older subjects to respond to questions by touching a computer screen. It gave them more privacy.
headline.main: Words That Wound

abstract: German authorities are reacting to calls to release information quickly about paintings, many looted, that were discovered in Munich.
snippet: German authorities are reacting to calls to release information quickly about paintings, many looted, that were discovered in Munich.
lead_paragraph: After an avalanche of criticism at home and abroad, the German government announced late Monday it will establish a task force to investigate, “as quickly and as transparently as possible,” the provenance of a cache of more than 1,400 artworks that are suspected of being traded or looted during the Nazis’ reign and that are now in the hands of authorities in Bavaria.

abstract: Only players with the most severe brain injuries will be compensated, and the estates of retirees who died before 2006 would be excluded, according to a draft of the proposed settlement.
snippet: Only players with the most severe brain injuries will be compensated, and the estates of retirees who died before 2006 would be excluded, according to a draft of the proposed settlement.
lead_paragraph: When the N.F.L. agreed to pay $765 million to settle a lawsuit brought by 4,500 retired players who said the league hid from them the long-term impact of concussions, lawyers in the case said all retirees would be eligible for a share of the settlement.
headline.main: Many Ex-Players May Be Ineligible for Payment in N.F.L. Concussion Settlement
headline.print_headline: Many Ex-Players May Be Ineligible to Share in N.F.L. Concussion Deal

abstract: Mr. Hudson, whose interception helped defeat the Baltimore Colts in the 1969 Super Bowl, requested that his brain and spine be given to researchers studying sports-related trauma.
snippet: Mr. Hudson, whose interception helped defeat the Baltimore Colts in the 1969 Super Bowl, requested that his brain and spine be given to researchers studying sports-related trauma.
lead_paragraph: Jim Hudson, the defensive back whose interception on a trick play helped propel the Jets’ storied upset over the Baltimore Colts in the 1969 Super Bowl, died on Tuesday in Austin, Tex. He was 70.

abstract: As a black woman, Dr. Wright was an unusual presence in medical institutions, but she said she never felt she was a victim of racial prejudice.
snippet: As a black woman, Dr. Wright was an unusual presence in medical institutions, but she said she never felt she was a victim of racial prejudice.
lead_paragraph: Dr. Jane C. Wright, a pioneering oncologist who helped elevate chemotherapy from a last resort for cancer patients to an often viable treatment option, died on Feb. 19 at her home in Guttenberg, N.J. She was 93.

abstract: The subject matter is wide in “The Oscar Nominated Short Films 2013,” an anthology released three weeks ahead of the Academy Awards.
snippet: The subject matter is wide in “The Oscar Nominated Short Films 2013,” an anthology released three weeks ahead of the Academy Awards.
lead_paragraph: Is the glass half-full or half-empty? In the movies, at least, the balance between hope and suffering usually tilts decisively toward hope. That is the predominant mood of “The Oscar Nominated Short Films 2013,” an anthology of three programs: live action, documentary and animation.

abstract: Mr. Rogers was born in the same hospital on the same day as Smokey Robinson, with whom he harmonized in high school and in the Hall of Fame singing group the Miracles.
snippet: Mr. Rogers was born in the same hospital on the same day as Smokey Robinson, with whom he harmonized in high school and in the Hall of Fame singing group the Miracles.
lead_paragraph: Bobby Rogers, who was born on the same day in the same Detroit hospital as the Motown crooner Smokey Robinson, with whom he harmonized in high school and eventually in the Hall of Fame singing group the Miracles, died on Sunday in Southfield, Mich. He was 73.

abstract: The Willem de Kooning Foundation and Gagosian Gallery plan to exhibit, and sell, 10 paintings by de Kooning in New York this fall to raise money for scholarly and educational programs.
snippet: The Willem de Kooning Foundation and Gagosian Gallery plan to exhibit, and sell, 10 paintings by de Kooning in New York this fall to raise money for scholarly and educational programs.
lead_paragraph: When Willem de Kooning was a struggling young artist and needed money, he would frequently sell a painting or sculpture as quickly as he made it. After his death in 1997, when the Willem de Kooning Foundation needed cash, it, too — like many artists’ foundations — would sell a work from its holdings, but always privately.

abstract: A ruling on the N.F.L.’s contention that the concussion-related lawsuits of more than 4,000 former players should not be heard in court is expected by this summer.
snippet: A ruling on the N.F.L.’s contention that the concussion-related lawsuits of more than 4,000 former players should not be heard in court is expected by this summer.
lead_paragraph: PHILADELPHIA — The two legal teams, the one for the N.F.L. and the one for the retired players suing the league for negligence and fraud, were stacked with top talent, including litigators who have argued in front of the Supreme Court.

abstract: Mr. Fisher created cartoons that managed to be erudite without being pretentious, requiring a general recognition of the world’s history and a healthy appreciation of irony.
snippet: Mr. Fisher created cartoons that managed to be erudite without being pretentious, requiring a general recognition of the world’s history and a healthy appreciation of irony.
lead_paragraph: Ed Fisher, whose culturally savvy cartoons, featured in The New Yorker for nearly 50 years, made wry sport of modern life, frequently matching images from history or folklore with captions in an up-to-date mode, died on April 3 in Canaan, Conn. He was 86.

abstract: Elderly people often need legal help, and law students need experience. Some health care institutions are making the match.
snippet: Elderly people often need legal help, and law students need experience. Some health care institutions are making the match.
lead_paragraph: Consider the geriatricians working at the Lakeside Senior Medical Center, an outpatient clinic at the University of California, San Francisco. Many of their patients, despite multiple chronic diseases and advanced age, have never filled out power-of-attorney documents or appointed someone to make health care decisions if they are unable to.

abstract: The noise at football games and other events is enough to cause permanent damage and to increase the likelihood of future damage. A few simple steps may help minimize the risks.
snippet: The noise at football games and other events is enough to cause permanent damage and to increase the likelihood of future damage. A few simple steps may help minimize the risks.
lead_paragraph: Earlier this fall, Seattle Seahawks fans at CenturyLink Field broke the world record for loudest stadium crowd with a skull-splitting 136.6 decibels.

abstract: More evidence that caregiving may improve health.
snippet: More evidence that caregiving may improve health.
lead_paragraph: The idea that caring for a chronically ailing or disabled family member might be good for you is so startling, so counterintuitive, that it sends researchers rummaging through their data to see where they went wrong.

headline.main: Are Caregivers Healthier?

abstract: A common question helps family members make sense of the confusion, desolation and powerlessness that so often defines the hospital experience, but leaves a newcomer to clinical medicine feeling vulnerable and violated.
snippet: A common question helps family members make sense of the confusion, desolation and powerlessness that so often defines the hospital experience, but leaves a newcomer to clinical medicine feeling vulnerable and violated.
lead_paragraph: The other residents and I sat in our blue scrubs with our attending physician in the windowless family meeting room just outside the intensive care unit. We had gathered around one end of the ovoid table with the family of the patient, two daughters and a son, at the other.

headline.main: ‘If This Were Your Mother, Doctor…’

abstract: The long-term consequences of U.S. budget cuts, in more than a few cases, are ominous. There is no better case study than Alzheimer's disease.
snippet: The long-term consequences of U.S. budget cuts, in more than a few cases, are ominous. There is no better case study than Alzheimer's disease.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Many Republicans, and Democrats, never thought the automatic across-the-board spending cuts known as sequestration would take effect. After all, they might produce dangerous, if unintended, consequences like potentially bankrupting the U.S. health care system, along with millions of families.
headline.main: Research Forgotten by Budget Cuts
headline.print_headline: Research Forgotten by Budget Cuts
byline.original: By Albert R. Hunt | Bloomberg View

abstract: The first government toxicology study of the supplement found that it caused cancer in lab animals, including an excessive number of liver and thyroid cancers.
snippet: The first government toxicology study of the supplement found that it caused cancer in lab animals, including an excessive number of liver and thyroid cancers.
lead_paragraph: Millions of Americans take ginkgo biloba supplements to boost memory and prevent dementia. Studies have never found any solid evidence that ginkgo does any such thing, but it did not seem to be doing much harm.

abstract: A sweeping new scientific initiative could help us understand dreams, memories and the very nature of consciousness.
snippet: A sweeping new scientific initiative could help us understand dreams, memories and the very nature of consciousness.
lead_paragraph: The Obama administration is planning a multiyear research effort to produce an “activity map” that would show in unprecedented detail the workings of the human brain, the most complex organ in the body. It is a breathtaking goal at a time when Washington, hobbled by partisan gridlock and deficit worries, seems unable to launch any major new programs.

abstract: In “The Other Place” Laurie Metcalf plays a pharmaceutical-company scientist who is convinced she has a brain tumor.
snippet: In “The Other Place” Laurie Metcalf plays a pharmaceutical-company scientist who is convinced she has a brain tumor.
lead_paragraph: As you watch “The Other Place,” a slick, potently acted drama by Sharr White that opened on Broadway on Thursday night at the Samuel J. Friedman Theater, it may strike you now and then that your mind is playing tricks on you. Facts that seem firmly established in one scene melt into vapor a few scenes later, leaving you with a vague itch to press pause to sort things out, or maybe rewind. Or both.

abstract: Could I now learn who they really were?
snippet: Could I now learn who they really were?
lead_paragraph: My mother was abandoned in a French orphanage in Fez in 1941. That year in Morocco, hundreds of people died in an outbreak of the plague; her parents were among the victims. Actually, no, they died in a horrific car crash on the newly built road from Marrakesh to Fez. No, no, no, my grandmother died in childbirth, and my grandfather, mad with grief, gave the baby away. The truth is: I don’t know how my mother ended up in a French orphanage in 1941. The nuns in black habits never told.

abstract: Under the agreement, the state will present all but the most severely mentally ill residents who have been kept in institutional homes in New York City with plans for moving into their own apartments.
snippet: Under the agreement, the state will present all but the most severely mentally ill residents who have been kept in institutional homes in New York City with plans for moving into their own apartments.
lead_paragraph: The administration of Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo agreed on Tuesday to give 4,000 mentally ill people who have been kept in institutional homes in New York City the opportunity to move into their own subsidized apartments, settling a contentious legal battle over the care for such patients that dragged on for a decade.

abstract: Even people who don’t care about football should be cheered that the Super Bowl is back at the Superdome.
snippet: Even people who don’t care about football should be cheered that the Super Bowl is back at the Superdome.
lead_paragraph: Let us be the first to welcome you officially to Super Bowl week, the annual gathering of N.F.L. worship that invades our planet and this year is destined to fill the streets of New Orleans with overindulged people imitating Ray Lewis’s celebration dance. There is nothing that can be done about this. We have already called Super Bowl week customer service. They said we just had to deal with it.

abstract: As temperatures in the region are expected to fall into the single digits, for many people whose boilers were flooded during Hurricane Sandy, home is as frigid as the outdoors.
snippet: As temperatures in the region are expected to fall into the single digits, for many people whose boilers were flooded during Hurricane Sandy, home is as frigid as the outdoors.
lead_paragraph: It was too cold for Daniel Choi to stay in his storm-gutted home in Gerritsen Beach, Brooklyn, so he left his two pet turtles, Michelangelo and Leonardo, behind to move in temporarily with friends. But on Wednesday, when he stopped by his home to feed them, he made an upsetting discovery. Plummeting temperatures in the still-heatless house had left the two turtles frozen under a sheet of ice.

abstract: If you are walking to improve your health, it’s time to stop strolling and pick up the pace, reports Gretchen Reynolds in this week’s Phys Ed column.
snippet: If you are walking to improve your health, it’s time to stop strolling and pick up the pace, reports Gretchen Reynolds in this week’s Phys Ed column.
lead_paragraph: Walking, fast or slow, is wonderful exercise. But now a first-of-its-kind study shows that to get the most health benefits from walking, many of us need to pick up the pace.

abstract: The Visiting Nurse Service of New York laid off 500 employees on Wednesday, part of the fallout from state scrutiny of enrollment practices that drew fit seniors into programs meant for the frail and disabled.
snippet: The Visiting Nurse Service of New York laid off 500 employees on Wednesday, part of the fallout from state scrutiny of enrollment practices that drew fit seniors into programs meant for the frail and disabled.
lead_paragraph: The Visiting Nurse Service of New York laid off 500 employees on Wednesday, part of the fallout from state scrutiny of enrollment practices that drew fit elderly people into programs meant for frail and disabled patients.

abstract: It is often said that A. .R. Gurney writes about a dying breed. But the characters in “The Dining Room,” the Westport Country Playhouse, are very much alive onstage.
snippet: It is often said that A. .R. Gurney writes about a dying breed. But the characters in “The Dining Room,” the Westport Country Playhouse, are very much alive onstage.
lead_paragraph: Sometimes it’s easy to tell which part of the 20th century we are seeing in “The Dining Room.” When one man mentions the horrors of “instant coffee on Eastern Airlines,” for instance, you know we’re in the era of the beloved hourly shuttle to Washington or Boston. At other times, it can be more difficult, as when a father complains, “The government is systematically ruining this country.”

abstract: Older veterans often are slow to recognize post-traumatic stress syndrome, even as it haunts many of them.
snippet: Older veterans often are slow to recognize post-traumatic stress syndrome, even as it haunts many of them.
lead_paragraph: Who knew much about post-traumatic stress syndrome in 1945? The term didn’t enter the official manual of psychiatric diagnoses until 1980; effective treatments didn’t become widely available until the late 1990s.
headline.main: No End to Trauma for Some Older Veterans

abstract: A college professor in Missouri recently ran a marathon while knitting a scarf over 12 feet long, weaving together pastimes first combined by an Englishwoman, Susie Hewer, in 2008.
snippet: A college professor in Missouri recently ran a marathon while knitting a scarf over 12 feet long, weaving together pastimes first combined by an Englishwoman, Susie Hewer, in 2008.
lead_paragraph: The long-distance friendship between Susie Hewer and David Babcock is held together by colored yarn and a world record few people knew existed.

abstract: Manhattan hospital patients are “catching” dementia in Lore Segal’s novel.
snippet: Manhattan hospital patients are “catching” dementia in Lore Segal’s novel.
lead_paragraph: In “Lucinella,” an eccentric little novel published in 1976, Lore Segal’s title character, a writer, confesses: “I’m no good at plotting. What I love is to get right down to the excruciations.”

abstract: Studies of Americans who take on in-home care are documenting health and financial repercussions.
snippet: Studies of Americans who take on in-home care are documenting health and financial repercussions.
lead_paragraph: Faced with the high cost of in-home care, many Americans end up providing care themselves for an aging parent or relative with a chronic condition. But by doing so, you may be putting your own finances, and even your health, at risk.

abstract: We can’t reduce medical errors without tackling the culture of shame.
snippet: We can’t reduce medical errors without tackling the culture of shame.
lead_paragraph: IT was probably our eighth or ninth admission that day, but my intern and I had given up counting. I was midway through my medical residency, already a master of efficiency. You had to be, or you’d never keep up. This one was a classic eye-roller: a nursing home patient with dementia, sent to the emergency room for an altered mental status. When you were juggling patients with acute heart failure and rampant infections, it was hard to get worked up over a demented nonagenarian who was looking a little more demented.

abstract: Mr. Hill, a receiver, was a rookie of the year, an all-N.F.L. and Pro Bowl player, and a key contributor to a Chicago Bears team that reached the league’s championship game.
snippet: Mr. Hill, a receiver, was a rookie of the year, an all-N.F.L. and Pro Bowl player, and a key contributor to a Chicago Bears team that reached the league’s championship game.
lead_paragraph: The Chicago Bears waited until the 15th round of the 1954 National Football League draft to select Harlon Hill, a receiver from a small Southern school. Hill was not exactly waiting to be chosen, because he had no thoughts of playing professional football.

abstract: Many caregivers don’t want the job — and feel guilty about that.
snippet: Many caregivers don’t want the job — and feel guilty about that.
lead_paragraph: Now and then, I refer to the people that caregivers tend to as “loved ones.” And whenever I do, a woman in Southern California tells me, I set her teeth on edge.
headline.main: The Reluctant Caregiver

abstract: People who have terminal diseases are living longer. Experts say simple strategies can make the most of the money at hand for those with foresight.
snippet: People who have terminal diseases are living longer. Experts say simple strategies can make the most of the money at hand for those with foresight.
lead_paragraph: PATRICK SKELDON, a commercial airline pilot, started having trouble walking in the autumn of 2003. His doctor thought he had a vitamin deficiency and prescribed supplements. When those didn’t work, the doctor referred him to a neurologist. The next year, he was told he had amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, more commonly known as Lou Gehrig’s disease. He was 59.
